 Hooton (Cheshire). The placenames derive from Old English <i>hōh</i> ‘heel, spur of land’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":19,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William Hooton was born about 1240, in Hooton, Cheshire, England. He married Mrs William de Hoton about 1284, in Hooton, Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. He died after 1272."},"et":{"about 1240–after 1272":"umbes 1240–pärast 1272","1252–Female":"1252–Surnud","1270–1323":"1270–1323","1287–Male":"1287–Surnud","1289–Male":"1289–Surnud","1290–1348":"1290–1348","1240–1272":"1240–1272","about 1270":"umbes 1270","1252":"1252","1240":"1240","1272":"1272","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1348":"1348","1259":"1259","1323":"1323","1289":"1289","1287":"1287","after 1272":"pärast 1272","about 1240":"umbes 1240","Hooton, Cheshire, England":"Hooton, Cheshire